##How can countries around the world cope with the three million masks doctors and nurses use every day?

For the front-line anti-epidemic medical staff, masks and other protective materials are their "armor. ". But in the global epidemic situation more and more severe, the material shortage has become a common problem faced by all countries.

World Health Organization director-general Tan Desai warned at a regular press conference on the 3rd that due to the increase in global demand as well as hoarding and improper use, medical gloves, masks, inhalers, goggles, masks and protective clothing and other prices soared, supply shortages, making the ability of countries to respond to the impact. "If we can't protect health care workers, we can't stop the spread of the new coronavirus, " he said.

World Health Organization estimates that health care workers worldwide need 89m surgical masks, 76m pairs of medical gloves and 1.6 m pairs of goggles a month. As things stand, the world's supply of personal protective equipment is expected to increase by 40% .

Tandsey called on the government to create incentives for manufacturers to expand production. This includes easing restrictions on the export and distribution of personal protective equipment and other medical supplies.

China, for example, is the world's leading producer of face masks, accounting for half of global production, but its exports have been severely curtailed by the Wuhan outbreak. To ease the pressure of medical shortages in the country, countries facing the burden of the epidemic are doing everything they can.

###Iran: Hoarding smuggled medical supplies carries the death penalty

The Middle East's beleaguered power is the most worrying. As of March 3, a total of 2,336 cases had been confirmed in Iran, including 77 deaths, with a case fatality rate of 3.3% . Lyne, WHO's executive director of Emergency Planning, also warned that the urgency of the Iranian health system's need for protective materials far outweighs that of other countries.

The country's foreign minister, Zarif, has appealed to the international community on social media for help, saying the country is in an emergency situation with N95 masks and three-layer masks, inhalers and nucleic acid test kits.

Supreme Leader Ali Khamenei on the 3rd ordered the army to help the health sector prevent and control the spread of the virus. The Ministry of Defence has also joined the production of face masks and disinfectants and has set up production lines in subordinate institutions. Mohammad Khatami, the Defence Secretary, had demanded that the department produce 20,000 masks and 20,000 litres of disinfectant a day.

On the same day, Farda reported that Health Minister Saee Namaki had written to Minister of Industry, mines and trade, Rahmani, on Feb. 29, denying previous claims that Iran could produce millions of masks a day, call it an "empty slogan" . Namaki said the ministry had received only 1m masks in the past week.

In addition, the government has arrested some suspects in an effort to crack down on hoarding and smuggling of medical supplies. If convicted of "spreading corruption" , they face the maximum penalty of death, or a minimum of five to 20 years in prison.

###South Korea: 130 million birds released free of charge

Industrial South Korea, where the 5,000 confirmed cases broke through early, is also in short supply. In Tiger, President Moon recently apologized to the nation for the government's failure to provide masks.

Moon made the deployment to solve the MASK PROBLEM: providing support for expanding production, developing a fair distribution program, and presenting the supply situation transparently.

Hong Nanji, Deputy Prime Minister and Minister of Planning and finance, proposed that the government would distribute 130 million masks free of charge to vulnerable groups, and strive to increase the daily production of masks across the country to 14 million, the supply rate through the public distribution network will be significantly increased (currently 50 percent) , with each bird selling for 1,200 to 1,500 won (7 to 9 yuan) .

Hong said that in order to crack down on malicious hoarding, major pharmacies will fully activate the monitoring system this week to prevent repeated purchases, and the government will provide production-increasing subsidies to mask manufacturers, and ensure the supply of raw materials and other support; Imports from Brazil, South Africa and elsewhere will also be considered.

South Korea's ruling Democratic Party, the government and Blue House held a meeting on the 4th, decided to basically cancel mask exports, to encourage weekend production to ensure supply. The meeting also discussed the system for ensuring the sharing of information on the safe use of medicines service DUR, and further explored options to prevent the repeated purchase of face masks and minimize queuing.

###Japan: Reserves Only 7.43 million, capacity requirement to double

Japan, with a population of 127 million, is already a big demander, but it has been hit hard by the outbreak and has even disappeared from retail outlets for a while.

Japan's government said at a budget meeting Thursday that the country had about 7.43 million masks as of March 2 and was studying their distribution. In view of the expansion of the epidemic, the opposition parties requested flexibility in the use of the country's current stockpile of new influenza countermeasures, such as masks.

The day before, the government had decided to allocate 2.285 billion yen (148 million yuan) from the Reserve Fund for 2019 to distribute face masks. Shinzō Abe, the prime minister, has been calling for increased production of masks since the end of last month, with the remainder to be bought by the state as a reserve.

Major Manufacturers have responded to the government's call to adopt a 24-hour production system to increase production of face masks. Sharpe, an electronics maker, is also expected to start making face masks in mid March, with a daily capacity of 150,000. Chief Cabinet Secretary Yoshihide Suga reiterated on February 26th that it expected to be able to supply 600m masks a month in March, double its January capacity.

But the Nikkei said the current "Hay fever" epidemic, even if the Japanese government to reach 600 million per month, can solve the supply shortage is uncertain.

###Italy: $10 MILLION GAP, emergency appeal to neighbors

Most European mask makers, including Italy, are based in China and have limited production capacity in Europe itself. Italy, which has the second highest number of confirmed cases outside the country, faces a shortfall of at least 10m masks. Italy has received 400,000 masks from South Africa and another 400,000 will arrive in Italy on the 4th, Luigi d'Angelo, head of Italy's civil defence ministry, told AFP on the 2nd, but that is not enough for such a serious outbreak.

In Lombardy 见 Lombardia，Reg. , where the outbreak is most severe, 200,000 masks are consumed in a day and regional hospitals have largely run out of supplies, he said. As Italy does not produce masks, it is contacting production countries such as Romania, Switzerland and the Netherlands.

Neighbouring France is also on the alert. President Maqueron said on twitter that France would seize all existing stocks and production capacity of masks and distribute them to public health professionals and those infected with the new coronavirus.

###US: CONSIDER USING WARTIME LAW to expand capacity

With 327m people in the US, the squeeze on supply and demand is palpable. The United States needs 3.5 billion N95 masks if there is a major outbreak, but stocks are only a tenth of that, HSS official Robert Kadlec said recently.

Supplies such as face masks and protective clothing are mostly made overseas, a major source of supply shortages.

The Food and Drug Administration (FDA) has broadened the use of face masks to include one commonly used by construction workers as a dust mask in its list of materials available for medical workers. The masks effectively filter 95% of particulate matter and are also used in hospitals and operating theatres to prevent bacteria.

Jerome M. Adams, the health department's chief medical officer, repeatedly urged the public not to snap up masks and to save them for those who really need them. He stressed that the risk to ordinary people was still low. Similar calls were made by Vice President Michel Pensée, who is in charge of the epidemic, and by Adjara Autonomous Republic, the HSS minister.

Adjara Autonomous Republic said in an interview Monday that the Donald Trump administration may use the war powers act to expand production of protective materials if necessary. In addition, the government is considering introducing the powers of the accompanying Defense Production Act to ensure that manufacturers give priority to the production of priority protective materials such as face masks and gloves. The US is under increasing pressure from the outbreak, with confirmed cases rising to 125, with deaths and many declaring a state of emergency.

Other countries with less manufacturing capacity are more focused on cutting costs. For example, the government of Thailand will impose restrictions on the number of masks that individuals, online or brick-and-mortar businesses and civil servants can hold, with the exception of public health and medical facilities. Those found in possession of excessive masks face up to seven years in prison and a fine of 140,000 baht. Russia has banned the export of several medical products, including face masks, in case of shortages at home.
